{
  "slug": "the-snubs-surprises-and-wtfs-of-the-2025-golden-globe-nomina",
  "title": "The Snubs, Surprises, and WTFs of the 2025 Golden Globe Nominations. Plus: Richard Gere!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Joanna Robinson"
  ],
  "published": "2024-12-09",
  "runtimeMin": 89,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Joanna Robinson read the 2025 Golden Globe film nominations the morning they dropped and sort the 'new Globes' (Fernanda Torres, A Different Man, a big Substance haul) from the 'old Globes' (Pamela Anderson, Angelina Jolie, a two-nomination Last Showgirl outdrawing Sing Sing). Emilia Pérez leads with 10, The Brutalist rebounds with 7, Sebastian Stan lands a double nomination, and Dune: Part Two limps to two. Then Sean talks to Richard Gere about Oh, Canada, his reunion with Paul Schrader 45 years after American Gigolo.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Snubs, surprises, and WTFs",
      "note": "new Globes vs. old Globes, category by category",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Emilia Pérez",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "10 nominations, the most of the morning. Sean reads it as the international body (300-plus overseas journalists) rubber-stamping a true contender after strong runs at the European Film Awards and abroad. Joanna is more mixed, noting the film has been critically pilloried since it hit Netflix and isn't guaranteed to bloom at the Oscars."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Brutalist",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "7 nominations, second only to Emilia Pérez, a rebound after Brady Corbet's film and Adrien Brody missed in some big precursor spots. Guy Pearce and Felicity Jones also land supporting nods; Sean, self-described scoutmaster of the Brutalist boys, is pleased."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Substance",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "A huge haul for a French body-horror movie: Best Comedy or Musical, two acting nods (Demi Moore and Margaret Qualley), and Coralie Fargeat in Best Director. The hosts call it the best possible news for Moore as she flirts with the last slot in a crowded Best Actress race."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anora",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Held serve, which is all it needs to do this early: in for Picture, Director, Actress (Mikey Madison), Supporting Actor (Yura Borisov), and Screenplay. Joanna thinks it has the 'everybody likes it' spot locked."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sing Sing",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Colman Domingo gets in, but Clarence Maclin is snubbed, bizarre given both won at the Gothams to the loudest reaction in the room. Fewer nominations than The Last Showgirl, which the hosts call not ideal; they blame the film's unglamorous, non-professional cast reading as too American for the Globes."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Apprentice",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sebastian Stan double-nominated, Best Actor Drama for this and Musical/Comedy for A Different Man, and the hosts' pick for biggest winner of the morning. They note nobody in the U.S. wants to touch the Trump movie (Stan was cut from Variety's Actors on Actors), which may push his campaign toward A Different Man."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Different Man",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Stan's Musical/Comedy nod, for the Aaron Schimberg dark comedy that just won Best Film at the Gothams. Sean holds it up as the model of using Marvel money to make something strange; both hosts prefer his work here."
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclave",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Best Drama, Best Director (Edward Berger), score, and Isabella Rossellini in Supporting Actress despite seven minutes of screen time. Joanna doesn't think it can win: its best shot is Screenplay, the field's only real adaptation. But she sees it taking the SAG ensemble as the undivisive meatball down the middle."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune: Part Two",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Only two nominations, and Denis Villeneuve snubbed in Director. The hosts, self-identified Dune fanboys, call it astonishing that at the Globes of all places the film underperformed this badly; they concede it basically never had a chance as part two of a planned trilogy."
        },
        {
          "title": "I'm Still Here",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Fernanda Torres in Best Actress Drama, the New Globes critics-and-international pick. The Brazilian journalists have run a forceful campaign for the Walter Salles film, and it's Joanna's heart pick to win International Feature."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Complete Unknown",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Timothée Chalamet in Best Actor and Edward Norton in Supporting for his Pete Seeger. Joanna previews her upcoming episode on the Dylan biopic (she liked it, no meltdown) and flags that Mangold's rewrite pumped up the Joan Baez and Susie Rotolo material."
        },
        {
          "title": "Challengers",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Four nominations including Zendaya, which the hosts cheer as keeping a fading contender alive. Joanna most wants it to win Score for the Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross club-music soundtrack, which she calls a genuine step in contemporizing film music."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hard Truths",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Marianne Jean-Baptiste left out of Best Actress, one of the morning's biggest snubs for a Mike Leigh performance that has won precursors and could take the BAFTA. Part of a run of overlooked Black performers the hosts flag, alongside Danielle Deadwyler and Aunjanue Ellis-Taylor."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Last Showgirl",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Two nominations, led by Pamela Anderson: a very old-Globes pick, and a cut below the newly critically acclaimed Globes, that outdrew Sing Sing and edged out Jean-Baptiste."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lee",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Kate Winslet nominated in Best Actress Drama for Ellen Kuras's wartime-photographer film. The hosts compare the push to the Andrea Riseborough / To Leslie campaign, run by some of the same people, though a bona fide movie star with a Globe nod is a different story."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nickel Boys",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "RaMell Ross snubbed in Director, a surprise given the film's momentum in cinematography and craft; very old-Globes to miss it. Aunjanue Ellis-Taylor also left out of Supporting Actress."
        },
        {
          "title": "We Live in Time",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean's last loser of the morning: if Andrew Garfield and Florence Pugh weren't getting in at the Globes, they aren't getting in anywhere. The A24 movie both hosts enjoyed looks shut out of the season."
        }
      ]
    },
